        "content": "That's a great question, Alex! Yes, climate change can indeed affect cloud formation during the condensation stage. As global temperatures rise, the atmosphere can hold more moisture, which might lead to changes in cloud formation. This can result in more frequent and intense storms in some regions, while others might experience less cloud cover and increased drought conditions. It's a complex interaction that scientists are continually studying.\n\nDoes anyone else have thoughts on how climate change might affect other parts of the water cycle?",
